Major Oil Marketers Associ­ation of Nigeria (MOMAN) said it is seeking consultation with the Ministry of Petroleum Resources and other industry stakeholders on the suspen­sion of the removal of petrol subsidy. President Muhammadu Bu­hari had last week announced the extension of the fuel subsidy removal for 18 months to pave way for more consultation. Some stakeholders see the move as a subtle way by the gov­ernment to put the burden on the incoming administration in the country. Akala’s Burial Rites Commences Feb 14, To Be Buried 18,… NiMET Warns Of Extreme Heats As Temperature Rises Across States Speaking in Lagos on Mon­day, Mr. Olumide Adeosun, Chairman, MOMAN, told newsmen that his association has been approached for reac­tion on the suspended removal of fuel subsidy. He said: “The members of the association are current­ly seeking to consult with the Ministry of Petroleum Resources, the Nigerian Mid­stream and Downstream Petro­leum Regulatory Authority and other industry stakeholders to understand exactly how this decision would impact the oth­er provisions in the Petroleum Industry Act (PIA) as well as market operations.